<img alt="Tiff in Tech 使用 Tiff in Tech 的 original sound 创作的 What is the different between edge ai chips and data center gpus?  I am going to explain it to you in a way that you never forget it when it comes up in a meeting, interview or talking to a friend. First of all, this is essentially like asking What's the difference between the chips in your phone and the ones in the cloud, and why does it matter?&quot; Edge AI chips are like the tiny brains inside devices like your smartphone or smart speakers. These chips are designed to work on their own, processing data right there on your device without needing to send everything to the cloud. For example, your phone can unlock just by recognizing your face, all thanks to the chip inside that handles it instantly and offline. #tech #technology #stem #techexplained " fetchpriority="auto" decoding="async" src="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/tos-maliva-p-0068/o8NBgKtbAwAQCA9BSeILIefMIRRe5AYMyAGeit~tplv-dmt-logom:tos-useast2a-v-0068/o89imeeMJAYNGUAQAIEIAtRIeKMLIomfBUebAB.image?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=R9Ly6eoTOw5%2Fb%2BHFZQRe8cSnCmA%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=-" imagex-type="react" imagex-version="0.3.10" srcset="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/tos-maliva-p-0068/o8NBgKtbAwAQCA9BSeILIefMIRRe5AYMyAGeit~tplv-dmt-logom:tos-useast2a-v-0068/o89imeeMJAYNGUAQAIEIAtRIeKMLIomfBUebAB.image?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=R9Ly6eoTOw5%2Fb%2BHFZQRe8cSnCmA%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 1x, https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/tos-maliva-p-0068/o8NBgKtbAwAQCA9BSeILIefMIRRe5AYMyAGeit~tplv-dmt-logom:tos-useast2a-v-0068/o89imeeMJAYNGUAQAIEIAtRIeKMLIomfBUebAB.image?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=R9Ly6eoTOw5%2Fb%2BHFZQRe8cSnCmA%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 2x" style="position: absolute; inset: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px; border: none; margin: auto; display: block; width: 0px; height: 0px; min-width: 100%; max-width: 100%; min-height: 100%; max-height: 100%;">

<img alt="Tiff in Tech 使用 Tiff in Tech 的 original sound 创作的 There’s a hidden system that runs the entire internet and almost no one knows about it. It’s called BGP.  What is BGP? (Border Gateway Protocol) BGP, or Border Gateway Protocol, is like the GPS of the internet. It’s the system that helps data figure out the best route to travel from one place to another across the massive network of the internet. How It Works: 	•	Internet is a Network of Networks: The internet is made up of thousands of separate networks, each run by different organizations (like Google, your local ISP, or a university). 	•	BGP is the Traffic Manager: BGP is the protocol that these networks use to tell each other which routes they know about. Think of it like a map where each network shares which destinations it can reach. 	•	Routing Decisions: BGP helps each network decide the best path for sending data to any destination. It’s like choosing the fastest or safest road to get somewhere. #tech #techtok #technology #stem #techexplained " fetchpriority="auto" decoding="async" src="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/okIsiiKAiAAvPQlAUEAB2BanUBIgPsxMyE8rC?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=JFXyiuCjaFWgkWw%2FBB7%2F1jEhwaM%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=-" imagex-type="react" imagex-version="0.3.10" srcset="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/okIsiiKAiAAvPQlAUEAB2BanUBIgPsxMyE8rC?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=JFXyiuCjaFWgkWw%2FBB7%2F1jEhwaM%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 1x, https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/okIsiiKAiAAvPQlAUEAB2BanUBIgPsxMyE8rC?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=JFXyiuCjaFWgkWw%2FBB7%2F1jEhwaM%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 2x" style="position: absolute; inset: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px; border: none; margin: auto; display: block; width: 0px; height: 0px; min-width: 100%; max-width: 100%; min-height: 100%; max-height: 100%;">

<img alt="Tiff in Tech 使用 Tiff in Tech 的 original sound 创作的 Why is every device you own running on the same old chip design? What if I told you… your phone, your laptop, your smartwatch even your fridge are all powered by the same kind of chip? It’s called an ARM chip and it’s everywhere. ARM stands for Advanced RISC Machine, and it’s not a brand it’s a blueprint. ARM Holdings designs the architecture, but companies like Apple, Qualcomm, and Samsung build their own chips based on it. ARM chips are based on RISC Reduced Instruction Set Computing. That means they run simpler instructions, but really fast and really efficiently. Think: fewer steps per task, but optimized for speed and low power. That’s why ARM powers most smartphones, tablets, and wearables. Even Apple’s M-series chips in Macs are now ARM-based. This year, over 70% of the world’s processors use this architecture. It’s the chip you never hear about but you use it every single day. #tech #techtok #techexplained #stem " fetchpriority="auto" decoding="async" src="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/tos-maliva-p-0068/o4EbIACAj6uNADDQKFAxfk3oehtIgEAgSyeGEq~tplv-dmt-logom:tos-useast2a-v-0068/oE3bvpQGfAE9tQA7ABRodFCx6iBJiEAgdfAIO8.image?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=utMVCaPcYdvsO5XWm%2F7MkT1uPUc%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=-" imagex-type="react" imagex-version="0.3.10" srcset="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/tos-maliva-p-0068/o4EbIACAj6uNADDQKFAxfk3oehtIgEAgSyeGEq~tplv-dmt-logom:tos-useast2a-v-0068/oE3bvpQGfAE9tQA7ABRodFCx6iBJiEAgdfAIO8.image?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=utMVCaPcYdvsO5XWm%2F7MkT1uPUc%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 1x, https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/tos-maliva-p-0068/o4EbIACAj6uNADDQKFAxfk3oehtIgEAgSyeGEq~tplv-dmt-logom:tos-useast2a-v-0068/oE3bvpQGfAE9tQA7ABRodFCx6iBJiEAgdfAIO8.image?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=utMVCaPcYdvsO5XWm%2F7MkT1uPUc%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 2x" style="position: absolute; inset: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px; border: none; margin: auto; display: block; width: 0px; height: 0px; min-width: 100%; max-width: 100%; min-height: 100%; max-height: 100%;">

<img alt="Tiff in Tech 使用 Tiff in Tech 的 original sound 创作的 The thumbnail you see on Netflix isn’t just a guess….  it’s calculated, personalized, and optimized by a machine learning system built to predict exactly what you’ll click? Here’s what’s happening behind the scenes: For every show or movie, Netflix doesn't make one thumbnail... they create dozens. Different characters, colors, even different emotional tones. And to figure out which one to show you, they use a contextual multi-armed bandit algorithm. It’s a type of machine learning that makes decisions by balancing two goals: ●Exploration : testing new thumbnails you might like ● Exploitation :  using thumbnails it already knows you engage with. #tech #technology #stem #techexplained #futuretech " fetchpriority="auto" decoding="async" src="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/owEUIAgAIExCAlB0GiAXfALtWhyCciAoEdgLBc?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=GYKn9nkOYVIZ7NLSc1AbbhjKr3I%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=-" imagex-type="react" imagex-version="0.3.10" style="position: absolute; inset: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px; border: none; margin: auto; display: block; width: 0px; height: 0px; min-width: 100%; max-width: 100%; min-height: 100%; max-height: 100%;" srcset="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/owEUIAgAIExCAlB0GiAXfALtWhyCciAoEdgLBc?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=GYKn9nkOYVIZ7NLSc1AbbhjKr3I%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 1x, https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/owEUIAgAIExCAlB0GiAXfALtWhyCciAoEdgLBc?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=GYKn9nkOYVIZ7NLSc1AbbhjKr3I%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 2x">

<img alt="Tiff in Tech 使用 Tiff in Tech 的 original sound 创作的 What if I told you one of the most annoying things on your screen… is also one of the most inefficient? That’s a modal pop-up. And we’ve all seen them. But here’s the thing, modal pop-ups aren’t just annoying. They freeze your UI, break accessibility, and completely disrupt user flow. Technically, a modal is what’s called a blocking UI element. It locks the rest of the app until you engage with it. That means the browser, or app, has to suspend all interaction outside that window. This causes problems for screen readers, mobile layouts, and even memory efficiency because the entire DOM behind that modal is still loaded, but unusable. And yet... developers keep using them. Why? They’re fast to build. Easy to copy-paste. And they create a false sense of “decision-making.” But in reality? Modals are often just bad UX pretending to be helpful. It’s outdated tech… that we still haven’t found a better way to replace. #tech #technology #stem " fetchpriority="auto" decoding="async" src="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/tos-maliva-p-0068/owCgUAGEIFIIAAfBeRAAQvALLCobZCqe5ejGkF~tplv-dmt-logom:tos-useast2a-v-0068/ooPiaAAUBKiABQAUAIEEINszQ4tBCzLy87Big.image?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=LLTh6HJ2WxxTLYcE5c%2BmEU%2BYo5M%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=-" imagex-type="react" imagex-version="0.3.10" style="position: absolute; inset: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px; border: none; margin: auto; display: block; width: 0px; height: 0px; min-width: 100%; max-width: 100%; min-height: 100%; max-height: 100%;" srcset="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/tos-maliva-p-0068/owCgUAGEIFIIAAfBeRAAQvALLCobZCqe5ejGkF~tplv-dmt-logom:tos-useast2a-v-0068/ooPiaAAUBKiABQAUAIEEINszQ4tBCzLy87Big.image?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=LLTh6HJ2WxxTLYcE5c%2BmEU%2BYo5M%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 1x, https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/tos-maliva-p-0068/owCgUAGEIFIIAAfBeRAAQvALLCobZCqe5ejGkF~tplv-dmt-logom:tos-useast2a-v-0068/ooPiaAAUBKiABQAUAIEEINszQ4tBCzLy87Big.image?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=LLTh6HJ2WxxTLYcE5c%2BmEU%2BYo5M%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 2x">

<img alt="Tiff in Tech 使用 Tiff in Tech 的 original sound 创作的 What is a transformer in AI? You mightve heard this trending term in a meeting, interview or talking to a friend. I am going to break it down for you so you never forget it again. It’s a type of AI model that’s really good at understanding context like how the meaning of a word depends on the words around it. Older models read one word at a time like reading with blinders on. Transformers? They read the entire input at once, and figure out which words—or even parts of an image—matter most. Here’s an example: If I say, “I unlocked the door with a paperclip. ” A transformer figures out that “with a paperclip” is probably modifying how I unlocked it… not what the door was made of. And because they can scale, meaning bigger models trained on more data get better, transformers became the foundation for modern AI. So yeah… transformers didn’t just change AI. They’re why it finally feels intelligent. #tech #technology #ai #stem #techexplained " fetchpriority="auto" decoding="async" src="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/o4ONgKfBEE2EIq0CgiOFABFUKBcAdiTAiAAhIo?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=pFZdjC04anUuKzFyRdKR5knhUWc%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=-" imagex-type="react" imagex-version="0.3.10" style="position: absolute; inset: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px; border: none; margin: auto; display: block; width: 0px; height: 0px; min-width: 100%; max-width: 100%; min-height: 100%; max-height: 100%;" srcset="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/o4ONgKfBEE2EIq0CgiOFABFUKBcAdiTAiAAhIo?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=pFZdjC04anUuKzFyRdKR5knhUWc%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 1x, https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/o4ONgKfBEE2EIq0CgiOFABFUKBcAdiTAiAAhIo?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=pFZdjC04anUuKzFyRdKR5knhUWc%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 2x">

<img alt="Tiff in Tech 使用 Tiff in Tech 的 original sound 创作的 What does airplane mode actually do on our phones?!  Technically, it disables all your device’s wireless communication: cellular, Wi-Fi, Bluetooth, GPS. But here’s the thing … it’s not because your phone is going to crash the plane. The real concern? Radio frequency interference. Cell phones emit signals in the same spectrum that airplanes use for navigation and communication… especially during takeoff and landing. It’s rare, but enough overlapping signals from hundreds of devices could potentially cause noise in the cockpit. But that’s only part of the story. #tech #technology #ai #stem #techeducation " fetchpriority="auto" decoding="async" src="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/tos-maliva-p-0068/okAHkInQGp6OfIemAIedANAAmLfkAgFRZ1MGWP~tplv-dmt-logom:tos-useast2a-v-0068/ogIBLjEQHDPenFSi5MADdgAISGCfASLAYQAtEf.image?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=nrYWy766ajCo65%2FlbTaEyke9W8Y%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=-" imagex-type="react" imagex-version="0.3.10" srcset="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/tos-maliva-p-0068/okAHkInQGp6OfIemAIedANAAmLfkAgFRZ1MGWP~tplv-dmt-logom:tos-useast2a-v-0068/ogIBLjEQHDPenFSi5MADdgAISGCfASLAYQAtEf.image?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=nrYWy766ajCo65%2FlbTaEyke9W8Y%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 1x, https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/tos-maliva-p-0068/okAHkInQGp6OfIemAIedANAAmLfkAgFRZ1MGWP~tplv-dmt-logom:tos-useast2a-v-0068/ogIBLjEQHDPenFSi5MADdgAISGCfASLAYQAtEf.image?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=nrYWy766ajCo65%2FlbTaEyke9W8Y%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 2x" style="position: absolute; inset: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px; border: none; margin: auto; display: block; width: 0px; height: 0px; min-width: 100%; max-width: 100%; min-height: 100%; max-height: 100%;">

<img alt="Tiff in Tech 使用 Tiff in Tech 的 original sound 创作的 What is SQL and why is it so important?  Every company has a data problem: too much of it, stored in too many places, and no easy way to get answers. That’s where SQL comes in. SQL, Structured Query Language, is how we extract, manipulate, and structure data stored in relational databases. Think millions of rows across multiple tables, users, orders, transactions, all linked by relationships. With just a few lines, SQL can JOIN tables, FILTER records, GROUP data, and even update massive datasets in seconds. It’s declarative, meaning you tell the database what you want, not how to compute it. And it works across systems…PostgreSQL, MySQL, SQLite, making it the universal language of backend infrastructure. If data is a mess, SQL is the tool that makes it useful. #tech #technology #stem #techeducation #techexplained " fetchpriority="auto" decoding="async" src="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/oAIj2UQNwA7bAeGfEgeqLyASA1IGVABRCWDQbI?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=OIbdJgL2pUQklJnCaXedQnH3%2F5k%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=-" imagex-type="react" imagex-version="0.3.10" srcset="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/oAIj2UQNwA7bAeGfEgeqLyASA1IGVABRCWDQbI?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=OIbdJgL2pUQklJnCaXedQnH3%2F5k%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 1x, https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/oAIj2UQNwA7bAeGfEgeqLyASA1IGVABRCWDQbI?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=OIbdJgL2pUQklJnCaXedQnH3%2F5k%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 2x" style="position: absolute; inset: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px; border: none; margin: auto; display: block; width: 0px; height: 0px; min-width: 100%; max-width: 100%; min-height: 100%; max-height: 100%;">

<img alt="Tiff in Tech 使用 Tiff in Tech 的 original sound 创作的 What is kubernetes? Here is a simple explanation so you can easily understand it whether in a meeting, interview etc.  Kubernetes is important because it makes running large, complex applications much easier and more reliable. Instead of manually managing every part of your app like starting and stopping services, handling traffic spikes, or fixing crashes. Kubernetes automates all of that. It works by running containers (small, packaged parts of an app) across a group of machines, organizing them into pods, and making sure everything stays healthy and balanced. If something breaks, Kubernetes fixes it. If your app needs to scale to handle more users, it does that too. It’s especially useful for modern apps built with microservices, where managing everything by hand would be overwhelming. #tech #techexplained " fetchpriority="auto" decoding="async" src="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/ocgBELEQCgAIMAjJAI1LeAhACntGBLvFcSf4eI?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=%2F%2FZx6sfhwDtwmWRNAPqWcLm7A00%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=-" imagex-type="react" imagex-version="0.3.10" srcset="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/ocgBELEQCgAIMAjJAI1LeAhACntGBLvFcSf4eI?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=%2F%2FZx6sfhwDtwmWRNAPqWcLm7A00%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 1x, https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/ocgBELEQCgAIMAjJAI1LeAhACntGBLvFcSf4eI?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=%2F%2FZx6sfhwDtwmWRNAPqWcLm7A00%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 2x" style="position: absolute; inset: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px; border: none; margin: auto; display: block; width: 0px; height: 0px; min-width: 100%; max-width: 100%; min-height: 100%; max-height: 100%;">

<img alt="Tiff in Tech 使用 Tiff in Tech 的 original sound 创作的 When you send a message or load a website, your data travels across a global infrastructure, one that most people never see. Over 99% of international internet traffic is carried by submarine fiber-optic cables laid across the ocean floor. These cables transmit data as pulses of light, using total internal reflection to bounce signals down glass strands at nearly the speed of light. Once your data reaches land, it's routed through a complex mesh of interconnected networks using protocols like BGP (Border Gateway Protocol), which determines the most efficient path to the destination. Routers act like traffic controllers, making real-time decisions to avoid congestion and outages. And in places where cables can’t reach, think rural areas, ships at sea, or remote islands, satellites and wireless networks take over, using radio frequencies to transmit data with higher latency but broad coverage. All of this happens in milliseconds, creating the illusion of instant connectivity! #tech #technology #stem #coding #ai #developer #techexplained " fetchpriority="auto" decoding="async" src="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/og3lImFzAKS8MGZeCADAQtfhjyPg2EHIAtE0fY?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=uTkr%2FfhlNVCt%2FDZ%2Bsa0U4HG9sno%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=-" imagex-type="react" imagex-version="0.3.10" srcset="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/og3lImFzAKS8MGZeCADAQtfhjyPg2EHIAtE0fY?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=uTkr%2FfhlNVCt%2FDZ%2Bsa0U4HG9sno%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 1x, https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/og3lImFzAKS8MGZeCADAQtfhjyPg2EHIAtE0fY?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=uTkr%2FfhlNVCt%2FDZ%2Bsa0U4HG9sno%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 2x" style="position: absolute; inset: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px; border: none; margin: auto; display: block; width: 0px; height: 0px; min-width: 100%; max-width: 100%; min-height: 100%; max-height: 100%;">

<img alt="Tiff in Tech 使用 Palali Music 的 sonido original 创作的 Let’s build a machine learning model that finds F1’s most underrated and overrated drivers.  GitHub: github.com/TiffinTech/f1_underrated_drivers I’m curious if you’ll agree with it. First, we’re building a Random Forest model that strips away team advantage to find truly underrated drivers. Our model looks at 8 key performance metrics: 	•	Qualifying position 	•	Teammate comparisons 	•	Grid vs. finish position 	•	DNFs and pit stops Here’s the cool part: we’re using a Random Forest Regressor. It learns the relationship between these metrics and points scored — but, and this is crucial — we deliberately exclude team names and car performance. The model analyzes: 	•	7 races from 2023 	•	3 races from 2024 That’s over 200 driver performances! Each driver gets two scores: 	•	Actual points scored 	•	Predicted points based on raw performance The gap between these? That’s our “underrated score.” So when a driver consistently outperforms their teammate, gains positions, and nails qualifying — but doesn’t have the points to show for it — our AI spots it. Let’s see the results… OK, do you agree with this? #tech #technology #stem #ai " fetchpriority="auto" decoding="async" src="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/oEEmsRCnkewYFiUVzADBtQAEJnBfAt7AjIANiD?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=Grhhh0ihfaiDt9sg7Q%2BiIawN9oI%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=-" imagex-type="react" imagex-version="0.3.10" srcset="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/oEEmsRCnkewYFiUVzADBtQAEJnBfAt7AjIANiD?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=Grhhh0ihfaiDt9sg7Q%2BiIawN9oI%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 1x, https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/oEEmsRCnkewYFiUVzADBtQAEJnBfAt7AjIANiD?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=Grhhh0ihfaiDt9sg7Q%2BiIawN9oI%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 2x" style="position: absolute; inset: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px; border: none; margin: auto; display: block; width: 0px; height: 0px; min-width: 100%; max-width: 100%; min-height: 100%; max-height: 100%;">

<img alt="Tiff in Tech 使用 Palali Music 的 sonido original 创作的 Let’s build an AI project that uses ML and Reddit data to make a stock market sentiment analysis.  At its core, it utilizes three main APIs:  PRAW for Reddit data collection, TextBlob for ML-based sentiment analysis, and yfinance for real-time stock data. The architecture implements a multi-layer approach. The data collection layer fetches posts from financial subreddits, while the ML layer processes text through TextBlob's pre-trained NLP model. This model analyzes linguistic patterns, contextual relationships, and negations to generate sentiment polarity scores ranging from -1 to 1. Data processing is handled through pandas DataFrames, where we aggregate sentiment scores and calculate statistical distributions. The backend uses Flask to serve an API. <img alt="Tiff in Tech 使用 Tiff in Tech 的 original sound 创作的 What happens when a robot doesn’t know what to do? No script. No instructions. Just a task — and it has to figure it out. But here’s the catch: In the real world, failure isn’t free. A bad decision can break something — or someone could get hurt. So how do we make robots that learn safely? Reinforcement learning lets a robot explore. Try something. Get a reward if it works, a penalty if it doesn’t. Over time, it builds a policy — its internal guide for what to do next. But not all robots learn this way. Some copy humans — that’s imitation learning. Others follow strict rules. The best systems blend all three. A delivery robot, for example, might use physics to stay upright, imitation to handle crowds, and reinforcement learning to react to surprises. To make that safe, we start with sim-to-real transfer — the robot trains in simulation first. Then we use human-in-the-loop learning — people guide and reinforce good behavior. And we add safety constraints — hard-coded limits on force, speed, and movement. So yeah — robots are learning. Just like we do. A little messy. A lot of math. And one mistake at a time. And that’s what makes it exciting. #tech #robotics #stem #ai " fetchpriority="auto" decoding="async" src="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/tos-maliva-p-0068/oAxBAonQKxXDvCteQMJgXfEUFEARHA5xxqH1AI~tplv-dmt-logom:tos-useast2a-v-0068/oI2ZVJDKIFAoQfC5yAEJA9EABqXLfRuKnxBHQZ.image?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=7ffkFyNJCXfewcc4u3iwMFjiBhA%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=-" imagex-type="react" imagex-version="0.3.10" srcset="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/tos-maliva-p-0068/oAxBAonQKxXDvCteQMJgXfEUFEARHA5xxqH1AI~tplv-dmt-logom:tos-useast2a-v-0068/oI2ZVJDKIFAoQfC5yAEJA9EABqXLfRuKnxBHQZ.image?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=7ffkFyNJCXfewcc4u3iwMFjiBhA%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 1x, https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/tos-maliva-p-0068/oAxBAonQKxXDvCteQMJgXfEUFEARHA5xxqH1AI~tplv-dmt-logom:tos-useast2a-v-0068/oI2ZVJDKIFAoQfC5yAEJA9EABqXLfRuKnxBHQZ.image?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=7ffkFyNJCXfewcc4u3iwMFjiBhA%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 2x" style="position: absolute; inset: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px; border: none; margin: auto; display: block; width: 0px; height: 0px; min-width: 100%; max-width: 100%; min-height: 100%; max-height: 100%;">

A Linear Regression model trained on historical qualifying lap data — it finds a line through the data that helps us predict future values 	2.	A performance factor system to capture unique team and driver strengths 	3.	A robust data preprocessing pipeline to handle missing data effectively  Our model uses Q1 and Q2 lap times as input features to predict Q3 times. <img alt="Tiff in Tech 使用 Tiff in Tech 的 original sound 创作的 Every time you swipe on your phone, you're falling for a psychological trick invented before the internet even existed.  Tech companies didn't design touchscreens around our needs - they exploited research that mapped exactly how our brains and fingers work. Heres how it works.. Back in 1954, long before computers were in every home, psychologist Paul Fitts made a discovery that would change everything about how we interact with technology today. He figured out exactly how our fingers work—specifically, the precise relationship between movement speed and accuracy when tapping targets of different sizes. This became Fitts' Law—and here’s the wild part: The reason buttons on your iPhone are around 9-10mm wide isn’t some Apple innovation. It’s because those 1950s experiments proved that’s  the ideal size for human fingertips. #tech #technology #stem #futuretech #techinnovation " fetchpriority="auto" decoding="async" src="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/oYA6EiRAz8UcBFBQUiSZKYEAAEZoDBrgAIiPA?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=9%2Bcu6Bi71nn5WR6pDFz0Vgnfuuk%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=-" imagex-type="react" imagex-version="0.3.10" srcset="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/oYA6EiRAz8UcBFBQUiSZKYEAAEZoDBrgAIiPA?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=9%2Bcu6Bi71nn5WR6pDFz0Vgnfuuk%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 1x, https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/oYA6EiRAz8UcBFBQUiSZKYEAAEZoDBrgAIiPA?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=9%2Bcu6Bi71nn5WR6pDFz0Vgnfuuk%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 2x" style="position: absolute; inset: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px; border: none; margin: auto; display: block; width: 0px; height: 0px; min-width: 100%; max-width: 100%; min-height: 100%; max-height: 100%;">

<img alt="Tiff in Tech 使用 Tiff in Tech 的 original sound 创作的 Here's something wild—every time you do anything online, your data travels the internet in tiny fragments called packets. But did you know that someone might be looking inside those packets? It’s called Deep Packet Inspection, or DPI, and it’s like X-ray vision for your internet traffic. So how does it work? Normally, internet routers just look at packet headers—essentially the digital envelope that says where data is going. But with DPI, network operators peek inside the envelope, examining the actual contents. ISPs use it to manage network traffic, cybersecurity systems use it to detect malware, and some governments use it for surveillance or censorship. #tech #technology #coding #stem #futuretech " fetchpriority="auto" decoding="async" src="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/tos-maliva-p-0068/oMECHizq8BACguBmIfvCAEAoiAh9s48sxDOAI1~tplv-dmt-logom:tos-useast2a-v-0068/oEH4BP7WCinEI1hX4AzoiBKHEnIeAA59DghA4j.image?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=uY1se%2BYsPsSSllFLnfoEmfzVhTY%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=-" imagex-type="react" imagex-version="0.3.10" srcset="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/tos-maliva-p-0068/oMECHizq8BACguBmIfvCAEAoiAh9s48sxDOAI1~tplv-dmt-logom:tos-useast2a-v-0068/oEH4BP7WCinEI1hX4AzoiBKHEnIeAA59DghA4j.image?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=uY1se%2BYsPsSSllFLnfoEmfzVhTY%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 1x, https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/tos-maliva-p-0068/oMECHizq8BACguBmIfvCAEAoiAh9s48sxDOAI1~tplv-dmt-logom:tos-useast2a-v-0068/oEH4BP7WCinEI1hX4AzoiBKHEnIeAA59DghA4j.image?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=uY1se%2BYsPsSSllFLnfoEmfzVhTY%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 2x" style="position: absolute; inset: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px; border: none; margin: auto; display: block; width: 0px; height: 0px; min-width: 100%; max-width: 100%; min-height: 100%; max-height: 100%;">

<img alt="Tiff in Tech 使用 Palali Music 的 sonido original 创作的 What if I told you the internet has a trust problem? Right now, when you check your bank account, your data travels through networks that mostly… trust each other. Limited verification, and often, no security checks at all. The Border Gateway Protocol, is like the internet’s GPS. But unlike your phone’s GPS, this 1980s system lacks built-in security. When a network says, “Send your Amazon traffic through me!”—other networks often just believe it. In 2022 alone, researchers spotted over 10,000 suspicious routing incidents. <img alt="Tiff in Tech 使用 Tiff in Tech 的 original sound 创作的 What is transfer learning in AI? Here is a simple explanation so you never forget it in a meeting or talking to someone. Researchers at Cornell discovered something fascinating about artificial neural networks: they found that the first layers of these networks learn universal features that work across almost any visual task. This is what we call transfer learning. Instead of starting from scratch every time, AI can take knowledge from one task and apply it to another. Here's what this means in practice: In a groundbreaking study at Google, researchers took an AI model trained on 1.2 million random images and repurposed it to identify medical conditions in x-rays. The transfer learning approach achieved 89% accuracy with just 10% of the usual training data needed. This isn't just theoretical - transfer learning is revolutionizing everything from drug discovery to climate science. Stanford researchers found it can reduce AI training time by up to 75% while using significantly less energy. So next time someone tells you AI learns from scratch each time - well, now you know better. #tech #technology #ai #stem #techexplained " fetchpriority="auto" decoding="async" src="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/tos-maliva-p-0068/owIBiigBAd8PCy1pvzQAA6EvhAECIAFcBeoOio~tplv-dmt-logom:tos-useast2a-v-0068/o8KvIQfgMGauoRR7AQ8dA9AAVWq6AeKiff0M1f.image?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=e3ZRFLzsznG1LASj6R%2FxMaDmKhE%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=-" imagex-type="react" imagex-version="0.3.10" srcset="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/tos-maliva-p-0068/owIBiigBAd8PCy1pvzQAA6EvhAECIAFcBeoOio~tplv-dmt-logom:tos-useast2a-v-0068/o8KvIQfgMGauoRR7AQ8dA9AAVWq6AeKiff0M1f.image?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=e3ZRFLzsznG1LASj6R%2FxMaDmKhE%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 1x, https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/tos-maliva-p-0068/owIBiigBAd8PCy1pvzQAA6EvhAECIAFcBeoOio~tplv-dmt-logom:tos-useast2a-v-0068/o8KvIQfgMGauoRR7AQ8dA9AAVWq6AeKiff0M1f.image?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=e3ZRFLzsznG1LASj6R%2FxMaDmKhE%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 2x" style="position: absolute; inset: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px; border: none; margin: auto; display: block; width: 0px; height: 0px; min-width: 100%; max-width: 100%; min-height: 100%; max-height: 100%;">

<img alt="Tiff in Tech 使用 Tiff in Tech 的 original sound 创作的 Why do versions of Y2K keep happening 🤔🤯 In 2014, the internet faced a critical breaking point that most people have never heard of - The 512K Day Crisis. But what exactly made this day so important? See, the internet works through routers that keep a special memory table of all possible paths to send data - like a massive address book. But in the 1990s, router manufacturers set a hard memory limit of 512K entries, thinking we'd never need more than that. This caused a massive problem when the internet grew beyond what anyone expected. Enter August 12, 2014 - now known as 512K Day. When the routing table exceeded 512K entries, routers worldwide began failing. Major websites went dark, internet service providers experienced outages, and thousands of networks started having mysterious problems. The internet was essentially running out of memory.  #tech #technology #coding #stem #developer #futuretech " fetchpriority="auto" decoding="async" src="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/o42g6vIphblAiqCAtEQAZBHEiMAIUdZBiSzUp?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=BpXIabJkljTjRmdcc54JvRz%2BrWs%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=-" imagex-type="react" imagex-version="0.3.10" srcset="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/o42g6vIphblAiqCAtEQAZBHEiMAIUdZBiSzUp?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=BpXIabJkljTjRmdcc54JvRz%2BrWs%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 1x, https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/o42g6vIphblAiqCAtEQAZBHEiMAIUdZBiSzUp?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=BpXIabJkljTjRmdcc54JvRz%2BrWs%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 2x" style="position: absolute; inset: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px; border: none; margin: auto; display: block; width: 0px; height: 0px; min-width: 100%; max-width: 100%; min-height: 100%; max-height: 100%;">

<img alt="Tiff in Tech 使用 Tiff in Tech 的 original sound 创作的 Right now, there's a global race to build a quantum internet under our oceans, and it could make hacking nearly impossible. Let me explain why this is wild. Today's undersea cables use light to send data with digital keys for encryption.  But here's the problem - hackers can secretly copy this data without leaving a trace. Enter quantum communication. It uses the rules of quantum physics to protect data. And here's the wild part - scientists just proved it works. In a recent breakthrough, researchers in Germany successfully transmitted quantum data while actively trying to hack it. Here's how: Instead of sending normal binary code, the system uses individual light particles - photons - to create an unhackable key. Try to spy on these photons, and they literally collapse. Even wilder? Scientists at Northwestern University just showed they can send quantum data through the same cables that carry our regular internet. Meaning we might not need to rebuild the entire internet to make it quantum-secure. With 99% of international data flowing through undersea cables, making them quantum-secure isn't just cool science - it's becoming a national security priority. So what do you think happens when hacking becomes nearly impossible?  Will it solve some cybersecurity problems or create new ones? #tech #technology #coding #stem #futuretech " fetchpriority="auto" decoding="async" src="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/tos-maliva-p-0068/oYSzBiCAiqFikCVAnoYE0gvAIocZBgA7CfXIWE~tplv-dmt-logom:tos-useast2a-v-0068/ocASAecKGCCPLAGIpiIVKUEFRESIwefgcTjmiA.image?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=Sh05ibS2yqy42k1tj6JGk80CNew%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=-" imagex-type="react" imagex-version="0.3.10" srcset="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/tos-maliva-p-0068/oYSzBiCAiqFikCVAnoYE0gvAIocZBgA7CfXIWE~tplv-dmt-logom:tos-useast2a-v-0068/ocASAecKGCCPLAGIpiIVKUEFRESIwefgcTjmiA.image?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=Sh05ibS2yqy42k1tj6JGk80CNew%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 1x, https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/tos-maliva-p-0068/oYSzBiCAiqFikCVAnoYE0gvAIocZBgA7CfXIWE~tplv-dmt-logom:tos-useast2a-v-0068/ocASAecKGCCPLAGIpiIVKUEFRESIwefgcTjmiA.image?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=Sh05ibS2yqy42k1tj6JGk80CNew%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 2x" style="position: absolute; inset: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px; border: none; margin: auto; display: block; width: 0px; height: 0px; min-width: 100%; max-width: 100%; min-height: 100%; max-height: 100%;">

<img alt="Tiff in Tech 使用 Tiff in Tech 的 original sound 创作的 This might be the most inefficient technology we still use today and it's in the name of every single file on your computer. Those three little letters at the end of your files? They're from a time when computers were so limited, they couldn't even handle long file names.  We're talking back in the 1980s when filenames could only be eight characters long, followed by a dot and three more characters. But here's the thing that's going to blow your mind - modern computers don't even need these extensions! They're smart enough to look inside files and know exactly what they are, using something called &quot;magic numbers. &quot; It works like this: Every file has a special code at the beginning that tells the computer what kind of file it is. It's like DNA for your documents. Your computer could just read this instead of relying on those three letters at the end. So why are we still using this ancient system? Because changing it would be like trying to convince everyone in the world to switch which side of the road they drive on... at the same time. Sometimes the most powerful force in technology isn't innovation - it's habit. #tech #techtok #technology #stem #FutureOfTech " fetchpriority="auto" decoding="async" src="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/tos-maliva-p-0068/oYwK9AkvQSAgKIQPEPLeCEg8TCfAicIfjAGzIp~tplv-dmt-logom:tos-useast2a-v-0068/okIjwSQe1E9IAQGbEgemLfASAiI3FASpCQPPhI.image?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=YHNnme4DCkP48KLHzuBCFe%2Bz25g%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=-" imagex-type="react" imagex-version="0.3.10" srcset="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/tos-maliva-p-0068/oYwK9AkvQSAgKIQPEPLeCEg8TCfAicIfjAGzIp~tplv-dmt-logom:tos-useast2a-v-0068/okIjwSQe1E9IAQGbEgemLfASAiI3FASpCQPPhI.image?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=YHNnme4DCkP48KLHzuBCFe%2Bz25g%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 1x, https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/tos-maliva-p-0068/oYwK9AkvQSAgKIQPEPLeCEg8TCfAicIfjAGzIp~tplv-dmt-logom:tos-useast2a-v-0068/okIjwSQe1E9IAQGbEgemLfASAiI3FASpCQPPhI.image?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=YHNnme4DCkP48KLHzuBCFe%2Bz25g%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 2x" style="position: absolute; inset: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px; border: none; margin: auto; display: block; width: 0px; height: 0px; min-width: 100%; max-width: 100%; min-height: 100%; max-height: 100%;">

<img alt="Tiff in Tech 使用 Tiff in Tech 的 original sound 创作的 Ever wonder who's in charge of the internet? Like, ACTUALLY in charge? While no one technically &quot;controls&quot; the internet, there are 13 root servers that act as its ultimate source of truth. Think of them like the internet's supreme court. When your device needs to find something online, these 13 servers are the final authority on where to go. And here's the wild part - the number 13 isn't random! It comes from a technical limit from the 1980s. Each lookup request can only be 512 bytes - about the size of a tweet. With each server needing 40 bytes... you get exactly 13 servers! But there aren't actually just 13 physical servers. There are hundreds of copies spread around the world, each working as part of a massive backup system! If all these root servers somehow went down at once with no backups, the entire internet would start breaking within hours. Your apps wouldn't work. Websites would become unreachable. Email? Forget about it. But the system is designed so that can't easily happen. When hackers tried to attack all 13 root servers in 2002, the backup copies kept everything running smoothly. Pretty smart, right? But wait - why can't we just make the packet bigger and have more root servers? Let me know in the comments if you want to hear that story next! #tech #technology #stem #techtok #FutureOfTech " fetchpriority="auto" decoding="async" src="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/tos-maliva-p-0068/owjE1FCeA9ffEnOkXPYvAgS6AAIIQAwNDhHAEg~tplv-dmt-logom:tos-useast2a-v-0068/ok6mjZrIv045iA5isBB1OQUvBAiAdCDiEAAPE.image?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=QRjdeh902P81IOdW2h3RoLCHWTg%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=-" imagex-type="react" imagex-version="0.3.10" srcset="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/tos-maliva-p-0068/owjE1FCeA9ffEnOkXPYvAgS6AAIIQAwNDhHAEg~tplv-dmt-logom:tos-useast2a-v-0068/ok6mjZrIv045iA5isBB1OQUvBAiAdCDiEAAPE.image?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=QRjdeh902P81IOdW2h3RoLCHWTg%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 1x, https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/tos-maliva-p-0068/owjE1FCeA9ffEnOkXPYvAgS6AAIIQAwNDhHAEg~tplv-dmt-logom:tos-useast2a-v-0068/ok6mjZrIv045iA5isBB1OQUvBAiAdCDiEAAPE.image?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=QRjdeh902P81IOdW2h3RoLCHWTg%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 2x" style="position: absolute; inset: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px; border: none; margin: auto; display: block; width: 0px; height: 0px; min-width: 100%; max-width: 100%; min-height: 100%; max-height: 100%;">

<img alt="Tiff in Tech 使用 Tiff in Tech 的 original sound 创作的 Something major is coming to your workplace in 2025: AI agents. ​ ​ Think personal assistants that can actually get things done – handling inventory, taking meeting notes, solving IT issues, all automatically. The wild part? You won't need to code to create them (thanks @Microsoft 365). These aren't just chatbots - they're task-focused helpers. ​ The future isn't AI vs us – it's about AI handling the routine so we can focus on what humans do best: create and innovate. <img alt="Tiff in Tech 使用 Tiff in Tech 的 original sound 创作的 Why did most major tech companies decide to make their AI assistants female?  Siri, Alexa, Google assistant - they all started with women's voices. And no, it wasn't a coincidence. If you're thinking of Siri or Alexa, you're probably hearing a female voice. But why is that? It's not just a coincidence. Back in the 1960s, a man named John Pierce was working at Bell Labs, trying to create the first computer-generated voice. And he made a key observation: people were already super comfortable getting help from women's voices. Why? Because for decades, telephone operators were exclusively female. But here's where it gets really interesting. Studies showed that people didn't just accept female voices – they actively preferred them in helper roles. We found them more welcoming, more trustworthy, and yes, less threatening than male voices. So when tech companies started creating AI assistants, they weren't just copying what came before – they were tapping into decades of social conditioning. Pretty wild, right?" fetchpriority="auto" decoding="async" src="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/tos-maliva-p-0068/o8PTbpZDRKQzEUiAFPC6VZ6BhiAA5BSiIELAm~tplv-dmt-logom:tos-useast2a-v-0068/oUBiwCQEvSpPSJAEzAiibATZ5KI9PU5A5BUm6.image?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=N08pOWOj8H%2BgxmcJ%2Bxy2aHBPe3U%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=-" imagex-type="react" imagex-version="0.3.10" srcset="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/tos-maliva-p-0068/o8PTbpZDRKQzEUiAFPC6VZ6BhiAA5BSiIELAm~tplv-dmt-logom:tos-useast2a-v-0068/oUBiwCQEvSpPSJAEzAiibATZ5KI9PU5A5BUm6.image?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=N08pOWOj8H%2BgxmcJ%2Bxy2aHBPe3U%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 1x, https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/tos-maliva-p-0068/o8PTbpZDRKQzEUiAFPC6VZ6BhiAA5BSiIELAm~tplv-dmt-logom:tos-useast2a-v-0068/oUBiwCQEvSpPSJAEzAiibATZ5KI9PU5A5BUm6.image?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=N08pOWOj8H%2BgxmcJ%2Bxy2aHBPe3U%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 2x" style="position: absolute; inset: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px; border: none; margin: auto; display: block; width: 0px; height: 0px; min-width: 100%; max-width: 100%; min-height: 100%; max-height: 100%;">

<img alt="Tiff in Tech 使用 Tiff in Tech 的 original sound 创作的 Have you ever felt like something's... off about the internet lately?  Like you're seeing the same content over and over, or conversations that feel weirdly artificial? You're not alone - and there's actually a fascinating theory about this. It's called the Dead Internet Theory.  See here's the thing: Studies show that over 40% of all internet traffic isn't human at all - it's automated bots. And some researchers think that number could be as high as 60%. Think about that: For every real person you interact with online, there might be a bot right next to them. But here's why this matters: The internet was built to be a space for human connection and creativity.  But now? AI can generate articles faster than humans can write them. Bots can create thousands of social media posts in seconds. And algorithms decide what content gets seen. #tech #technology #stem #techexplained #futuretech " fetchpriority="auto" decoding="async" src="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/tos-maliva-p-0068/oIPJEhNwQAcWE3lIIzAlaCAQAjLfnSelWgeGPI~tplv-dmt-logom:tos-useast2a-v-0068/oQxuIfiJgPtjAIufPAQEuhLBI0ClScewERAkGA.image?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=UCsdo4xyFbcD0mtCKjFmKzR7qIU%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=-" imagex-type="react" imagex-version="0.3.10" srcset="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/tos-maliva-p-0068/oIPJEhNwQAcWE3lIIzAlaCAQAjLfnSelWgeGPI~tplv-dmt-logom:tos-useast2a-v-0068/oQxuIfiJgPtjAIufPAQEuhLBI0ClScewERAkGA.image?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=UCsdo4xyFbcD0mtCKjFmKzR7qIU%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 1x, https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/tos-maliva-p-0068/oIPJEhNwQAcWE3lIIzAlaCAQAjLfnSelWgeGPI~tplv-dmt-logom:tos-useast2a-v-0068/oQxuIfiJgPtjAIufPAQEuhLBI0ClScewERAkGA.image?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=UCsdo4xyFbcD0mtCKjFmKzR7qIU%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 2x" style="position: absolute; inset: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px; border: none; margin: auto; display: block; width: 0px; height: 0px; min-width: 100%; max-width: 100%; min-height: 100%; max-height: 100%;">

<img alt="Tiff in Tech 使用 Tiff in Tech 的 original sound 创作的 There's something weird happening to the internet right now, and almost no one is talking about it. We're running out of addresses - not physical addresses, but IP addresses.  You know, those number sequences that help computers find each other online? Here's the thing: When the internet was built, they created a system called IPv4 that allows for about 4 billion unique addresses. In 1981, that seemed like way more than we'd ever need. But now? Yeah, we've basically used them all up. Think of it like a phone number system. Imagine if we could only use 7 digits. Eventually, we'd run out of new numbers to give people. That's exactly what's happening with IP addresses. And when we run out completely?  New devices won't be able to connect to the internet properly, and services like video calls and online gaming will start breaking down because devices can't establish direct connections anymore. The solution exists - it's called IPv6, and it can handle a mind-blowing 340 undecillion addresses. #tech #stem #futuretech #coding " fetchpriority="auto" decoding="async" src="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/tos-maliva-p-0068/o0IDnkAhyhmUECJfdYRB0oAAECJGRtAEsQfFRR~tplv-dmt-logom:tos-useast2a-v-0068/oMAQAf1lBgCziAJCyRiRKmEGyBEIkDwoyUISIA.image?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=H8%2BJL1z%2FewG654KB7pNGfvvFTI8%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=-" imagex-type="react" imagex-version="0.3.10" srcset="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/tos-maliva-p-0068/o0IDnkAhyhmUECJfdYRB0oAAECJGRtAEsQfFRR~tplv-dmt-logom:tos-useast2a-v-0068/oMAQAf1lBgCziAJCyRiRKmEGyBEIkDwoyUISIA.image?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=H8%2BJL1z%2FewG654KB7pNGfvvFTI8%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 1x, https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/tos-maliva-p-0068/o0IDnkAhyhmUECJfdYRB0oAAECJGRtAEsQfFRR~tplv-dmt-logom:tos-useast2a-v-0068/oMAQAf1lBgCziAJCyRiRKmEGyBEIkDwoyUISIA.image?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=H8%2BJL1z%2FewG654KB7pNGfvvFTI8%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 2x" style="position: absolute; inset: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px; border: none; margin: auto; display: block; width: 0px; height: 0px; min-width: 100%; max-width: 100%; min-height: 100%; max-height: 100%;">

<img alt="Tiff in Tech 使用 Tiff in Tech 的 original sound 创作的 Could the government actually turn off our internet?  Well... yes and no. <img alt="Tiff in Tech 使用 Tiff in Tech 的 original sound 创作的 What is zero-proof-knowledge and why is it such a big deal?  Instead of sending your actual password, your device turns it into a massive number that can't be reversed. When you log in, the website sends a random challenge, and your device responds with mathematical proof - like solving a puzzle that only someone with your password could solve. Companies like BMW are already using this for massive transactions. They can prove they made valid payments for thousands of parts without revealing any details. Their competitors see nothing, but everyone knows the transaction is legit. The best part? Your password never leaves your device. If a company gets hacked, your password can't be stolen because they never had it. And with billions of passwords leaked last year, that's a game-changer. #tech #stem #futuretech " fetchpriority="auto" decoding="async" src="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/tos-maliva-p-0068/ogYGLEfcdI7AcEbNIAAtIesXS1DYPQAghCLjge~tplv-dmt-logom:tos-useast2a-v-0068/oIAAdQAXNQPA8fZ1ykQlEWDIjCtMOgbSoI8Eee.image?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=2ZJR%2FI%2Fpm8nEa3f44n%2Fqe4awcO4%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=-" imagex-type="react" imagex-version="0.3.10" srcset="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/tos-maliva-p-0068/ogYGLEfcdI7AcEbNIAAtIesXS1DYPQAghCLjge~tplv-dmt-logom:tos-useast2a-v-0068/oIAAdQAXNQPA8fZ1ykQlEWDIjCtMOgbSoI8Eee.image?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=2ZJR%2FI%2Fpm8nEa3f44n%2Fqe4awcO4%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 1x, https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/tos-maliva-p-0068/ogYGLEfcdI7AcEbNIAAtIesXS1DYPQAghCLjge~tplv-dmt-logom:tos-useast2a-v-0068/oIAAdQAXNQPA8fZ1ykQlEWDIjCtMOgbSoI8Eee.image?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=2ZJR%2FI%2Fpm8nEa3f44n%2Fqe4awcO4%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 2x" style="position: absolute; inset: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px; border: none; margin: auto; display: block; width: 0px; height: 0px; min-width: 100%; max-width: 100%; min-height: 100%; max-height: 100%;">

<img alt="Tiff in Tech 使用 Palali Music 的 sonido original 创作的 Even using incognito mode won’t protect you from this. But there is a browser that allows your to turn it off (for the most part)  Every website you visit is collecting over 50 pieces of invisible information about you right now. Not just your location or device - but things like how your keyboard types, how your mouse moves, even how your battery drains. Together, they create something called a digital fingerprint, and it can identify you with 99% accuracy.  And here's where it gets interesting - companies aren't just collecting this data, they're selling it. Advertisers, data brokers, and analytics companies all want your digital fingerprint because it helps them build detailed profiles of your habits. They use this to predict what you'll buy, when you'll buy it, and how much you'll spend. The wild part? Unlike cookies, you can't delete this. Clear your history, use incognito mode, even switch browsers - your fingerprint follows you. Every website you visit becomes another piece of your digital shadow, painting an increasingly detailed picture of your online life. #tech #technology #stem #futuretech " fetchpriority="auto" decoding="async" src="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/ocm9kPAEeAEeAiGvISzIEvQguLj9JC6AeSIICo?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=oSBIaEa7%2F7NmSErxjRBrqNX3k4c%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=-" imagex-type="react" imagex-version="0.3.10" srcset="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/ocm9kPAEeAEeAiGvISzIEvQguLj9JC6AeSIICo?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=oSBIaEa7%2F7NmSErxjRBrqNX3k4c%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 1x, https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/ocm9kPAEeAEeAiGvISzIEvQguLj9JC6AeSIICo?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=oSBIaEa7%2F7NmSErxjRBrqNX3k4c%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 2x" style="position: absolute; inset: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px; border: none; margin: auto; display: block; width: 0px; height: 0px; min-width: 100%; max-width: 100%; min-height: 100%; max-height: 100%;">

<img alt="Tiff in Tech 使用 Tiff in Tech 的 original sound 创作的 Have you ever wondered how your phone knows which signals are meant for YOU among the millions flying through the air right now? Every second, there are countless phone calls zooming through the space around us. But your phone finds exactly what it needs through a process called frequency-division multiplexing. Here's how it works: Your phone and cell towers communicate using unique frequency bands and digital codes. - kind of like having a private language that only they understand. When I make a call, my phone scrambles the signal using this special code. Other phones detect these radio waves, but can't decipher them. But here's the weird part - sometimes your phone shows full bars, but nothing works! This is because they only measure downlink RSSI. You could have perfect reception, but if thousands of phones are overwhelming the tower's processing capacity or your uplink is weak, you'll still have connection issues. #tech #technology #coding #stem " fetchpriority="auto" decoding="async" src="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/tos-maliva-p-0068/oI1DSHQQE3DAgJeFacCbEnSQkA9BREAAICG9fE~tplv-dmt-logom:tos-useast2a-v-0068/oEEBIACAjpLAAcGPYLCQecqu0hfIvIAgSe0DEa.image?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=%2BXFcaYuIKVNb4zF9Fx81PKeaNNI%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=-" imagex-type="react" imagex-version="0.3.10" srcset="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/tos-maliva-p-0068/oI1DSHQQE3DAgJeFacCbEnSQkA9BREAAICG9fE~tplv-dmt-logom:tos-useast2a-v-0068/oEEBIACAjpLAAcGPYLCQecqu0hfIvIAgSe0DEa.image?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=%2BXFcaYuIKVNb4zF9Fx81PKeaNNI%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 1x, https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/tos-maliva-p-0068/oI1DSHQQE3DAgJeFacCbEnSQkA9BREAAICG9fE~tplv-dmt-logom:tos-useast2a-v-0068/oEEBIACAjpLAAcGPYLCQecqu0hfIvIAgSe0DEa.image?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=%2BXFcaYuIKVNb4zF9Fx81PKeaNNI%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 2x" style="position: absolute; inset: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px; border: none; margin: auto; display: block; width: 0px; height: 0px; min-width: 100%; max-width: 100%; min-height: 100%; max-height: 100%;">

<img alt="Tiff in Tech 使用 Palali Music 的 sonido original 创作的 You might think the internet was built by some giant tech company, or maybe a government agency. But the system that powers literally everything you do online? It was created by two guys who were trying to solve an impossible problem. #tech #technology #coding #stem #futuretech  In 1974, different computer networks were like countries with completely different postal systems. If you were on one network, you couldn't send anything to another. They spoke different languages, used different rules - everything. Then these two guys [Vint Cerf and Bob Kahn] came up with an idea that changed everything: break all information into tiny pieces called packets." fetchpriority="auto" decoding="async" src="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/tos-maliva-p-0068/oE8IL1FyBDyguJcCfaFEQRQERAxUAjafEACnAW~tplv-dmt-logom:tos-useast2a-v-0068/oAwFAECkInRJERAaefvaCQW7nLAy6DRlgAEQAB.image?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=%2FHcL7GtJ9L7VvKfL3NCrilknZsc%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=-" imagex-type="react" imagex-version="0.3.10" srcset="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/tos-maliva-p-0068/oE8IL1FyBDyguJcCfaFEQRQERAxUAjafEACnAW~tplv-dmt-logom:tos-useast2a-v-0068/oAwFAECkInRJERAaefvaCQW7nLAy6DRlgAEQAB.image?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=%2FHcL7GtJ9L7VvKfL3NCrilknZsc%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 1x, https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/tos-maliva-p-0068/oE8IL1FyBDyguJcCfaFEQRQERAxUAjafEACnAW~tplv-dmt-logom:tos-useast2a-v-0068/oAwFAECkInRJERAaefvaCQW7nLAy6DRlgAEQAB.image?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=%2FHcL7GtJ9L7VvKfL3NCrilknZsc%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 2x" style="position: absolute; inset: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px; border: none; margin: auto; display: block; width: 0px; height: 0px; min-width: 100%; max-width: 100%; min-height: 100%; max-height: 100%;">

<img alt="Tiff in Tech 使用 Anderson .Paak 的 Make It Better (Instrumental) 创作的 Here's something wild - the cloud wasn't invented by tech giants. It actually started way back in the 1960s with something called time-sharing. See, computers used to be MASSIVE and cost millions. So companies would rent out computing time, kind of like splitting a vacation home with strangers. You'd get your slice of computing power when you needed it. Fast forward to 2006. Amazon had this fascinating problem - they'd built this HUGE computing infrastructure for their holiday shopping season, but it sat mostly empty the rest of the year. Then someone had a brilliant idea: &quot;What if we rented out our extra capacity?&quot; That's how Amazon Web Services was born. But here's where it gets really interesting. Traditional servers are like having a whole house to yourself - you pay for everything, even the rooms you don't use. Modern cloud computing? It's more like a magical house that grows and shrinks exactly as you need it. We've gone from sharing time on massive computers, to renting virtual servers, to not thinking about servers at all (using containers). And that's transforming how we build everything from your favorite apps to entire companies." fetchpriority="auto" decoding="async" src="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/oYIA2OWInE2AfgjPiSQADFECAwDPreAaEfm7HS?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=%2BnoVgwErAzJb5PnAZWqAqCzWUYs%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=-" imagex-type="react" imagex-version="0.3.10" srcset="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/oYIA2OWInE2AfgjPiSQADFECAwDPreAaEfm7HS?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=%2BnoVgwErAzJb5PnAZWqAqCzWUYs%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 1x, https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/oYIA2OWInE2AfgjPiSQADFECAwDPreAaEfm7HS?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=%2BnoVgwErAzJb5PnAZWqAqCzWUYs%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 2x" style="position: absolute; inset: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px; border: none; margin: auto; display: block; width: 0px; height: 0px; min-width: 100%; max-width: 100%; min-height: 100%; max-height: 100%;">

<img alt="Tiff in Tech 使用 Tiff in Tech 的 original sound 创作的 Would you live in this underwater habitat?  In 2025, humans might finally have a new home - underwater. Right now, scientists can only spend 10 minutes working at deep depths before needing 6 hours to decompress. This could turn those minutes into months of research time. This is Vanguard, and it's about to change how we explore our oceans. Here's what makes it work: Imagine a shipping container-sized home that keeps you alive 100 meters underwater. The secret? It's built by robots. These aren't just any robots. They're using wire-arc additive manufacturing - basically 3D printing meets welding. Six robotic arms work together to build massive pressure-resistant hulls up to 6 meters wide. But here's the wild part - inside Vanguard, you're breathing 98% helium. Why? Because at that depth, nitrogen becomes toxic. But helium creates a whole new problem.  It's so thermally conductive that they have to heat it to 31°C just to keep the habitat comfortable! The tech keeping you alive runs on floating solar farms and specially designed underwater batteries - because normal ones? Helium would destroy them. This isn't just cool tech - it's opening up the 90% of ocean biodiversity we've never been able to properly study. <img alt="Tiff in Tech 使用 Anderson .Paak 的 Make It Better (Instrumental) 创作的 What if I told you that most of the encryption protecting our internet is about to become... breakable? Right now, our online security uses mathematical puzzles that are basically impossible for regular computers to solve. Like, it would take them thousands of years. But quantum computers? They could crack these puzzles in weeks. Maybe even days. That's why this is fascinating - a team of cryptographers, led by Joppe Bos, created something called CRYSTALS-Kyber. Instead of using traditional math problems, it uses something called lattice-based cryptography. Imagine a grid in multiple dimensions, with thousands of points. Your secret message is hidden using math that involves finding specific paths between these points. Even quantum computers get lost trying to solve it! The coolest part? This isn't just theoretical. Google's Chrome browser is already using it. Your future credit cards will use it. Even your car might use it. This is how we quantum-proof the internet - not with bigger locks, but with better math. #tech #technology #quantumcomputing #coding #stem #techexplained " fetchpriority="auto" decoding="async" src="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/oIQ1fUQdfAEVYMBNBBRn7HBk1iBJiEbsXdWIWz?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=U4Ud2o%2BCunEiLhmygMfjsWtnHnc%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=-" imagex-type="react" imagex-version="0.3.10" srcset="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/oIQ1fUQdfAEVYMBNBBRn7HBk1iBJiEbsXdWIWz?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=U4Ud2o%2BCunEiLhmygMfjsWtnHnc%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 1x, https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/oIQ1fUQdfAEVYMBNBBRn7HBk1iBJiEbsXdWIWz?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=U4Ud2o%2BCunEiLhmygMfjsWtnHnc%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 2x" style="position: absolute; inset: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px; border: none; margin: auto; display: block; width: 0px; height: 0px; min-width: 100%; max-width: 100%; min-height: 100%; max-height: 100%;">

<img alt="Tiff in Tech 使用 Palali Music 的 sonido original 创作的 When you hear &quot;computer&quot; today, you probably think of something like this. But what if I told you that the first computers looked nothing like this? They actually looked like this. Here's something wild: &quot;Computer&quot; wasn't a machine - it was a job title. Like &quot;baker&quot; or &quot;teacher”, a computer was someone who computed things. In the 1940s, newspapers ran ads for &quot;computers wanted&quot;- seeking mathematicians, who could perform complex calculations by hand. And we're talking serious math here - missile trajectories, satellite orbits, astronomical data. Using mechanical calculators and their incredible minds, they spent days on calculations where even tiny errors could have huge consequences. But here's where it gets really interesting. When the first electronic computer, ENIAC, was built in 1945, who do you think they got to program it? Six of these human computers. But forget javascript and Python - they had to program by physically connecting cables and flipping switches. <img alt="Tiff in Tech 使用 Tiff in Tech 的 original sound 创作的 In 1985, there was a massive problem threatening to break the entire internet. But most people don't know about the woman who solved it - Radia Perlman. See, early computer networks had a critical flaw. T o make sure messages got through, networks would create multiple paths between computers. But this caused an explosive problem called a broadcast storm - messages would loop endlessly until the entire network collapsed. Enter Radia Perlman. In just one weekend, she wrote the Spanning Tree Protocol - an algorithm that automatically prevents these loops. And here's the wild part - it's still running in almost every network today. Perlman says her more important work was making networks &quot;self-healing&quot;  What Perlman considers her more significant contribution was developing &quot;Network Fault T olerance&quot; protocols. These algorithms automatically detect network failures and reroute traffic in milliseconds - without any human intervention.  Her work on the IS-IS (Intermediate System to Intermediate System) protocol became fundamental to how large networks maintain reliability. #tech #technology #coding #stem #futuretech " fetchpriority="auto" decoding="async" src="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/o8frzupEtBgio55EAIpA3AAP8ldotzGuBCItiB?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=G4OVWlzkVmMWp8VXpryh5dwX1jc%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=-" imagex-type="react" imagex-version="0.3.10" srcset="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/o8frzupEtBgio55EAIpA3AAP8ldotzGuBCItiB?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=G4OVWlzkVmMWp8VXpryh5dwX1jc%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 1x, https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/o8frzupEtBgio55EAIpA3AAP8ldotzGuBCItiB?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=G4OVWlzkVmMWp8VXpryh5dwX1jc%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 2x" style="position: absolute; inset: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px; border: none; margin: auto; display: block; width: 0px; height: 0px; min-width: 100%; max-width: 100%; min-height: 100%; max-height: 100%;">
https://www.tiktok.com/@tiffintech/video/7452096255280352518
<img alt="Tiff in Tech 使用 Tiff in Tech 的 original sound 创作的 This might be one of the most brilliant security features ever invented. And you're using it every single day without even knowing it. When you type your password into a website, you probably think it's stored somewhere, right? Wrong. What's actually stored is complete gibberish - and that's exactly how it should be. Let's say your password is &quot;DogLover123&quot; . When you create an account, the website runs it through something called SHA-256 - a cryptographic hash function that's basically a superhero of the internet. It puts your password through 64 rounds of mathematical operations. So &quot;DogLover123&quot; becomes this: &quot;8d969eef6ecad3c29a3a629280e686cf0c3f5d5a86aff3ca12020c923adc6c92&quot; This 256-bit output looks random, but it's actually the result of precise mathematical chaos. But wait - if websites don't know your actual password, how do they check if you typed it correctly? Here's where it gets interesting: SHA-256 will always create the exact same output for the same input. So when you log in, they run your password through those same 64 rounds of mathematical operations and check if the gibberish matches. And here's what makes SHA-256 incredible - it's mathematically impossible to find two passwords that create the same output. Even changing one letter creates a completely different hash. #tech #technology #stem #techexplained " fetchpriority="auto" decoding="async" src="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/oM2qAoiABKIiZiJEsGUApLEQrIBBiNuQ2DAhP?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=8Mw5t1gi4DRoNT2wvP8QlnyXOqk%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=-" imagex-type="react" imagex-version="0.3.10" srcset="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/oM2qAoiABKIiZiJEsGUApLEQrIBBiNuQ2DAhP?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=8Mw5t1gi4DRoNT2wvP8QlnyXOqk%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 1x, https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/oM2qAoiABKIiZiJEsGUApLEQrIBBiNuQ2DAhP?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=8Mw5t1gi4DRoNT2wvP8QlnyXOqk%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 2x" style="position: absolute; inset: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px; border: none; margin: auto; display: block; width: 0px; height: 0px; min-width: 100%; max-width: 100%; min-height: 100%; max-height: 100%;">

<img alt="Tiff in Tech 使用 Tiff in Tech 的 original sound 创作的 Ever wondered who invented the text message? Well - like most world-changing inventions, it was a bit complicated.. Let me explain.   In 1984, two engineers were working when they had an idea: what if phones could send short written messages?  But here's what's fascinating - they noticed something when studying postcards. Most messages people wrote naturally fell under 160 characters. That's why early texts had that limit!  Then, on December 3rd, 1992, something huge happened. A 22-year-old programmer named Neil Papworth sent the world's first text message. Want to know what it said? &quot;Merry Christmas.&quot;   But here's the plot twist - Papworth wasn't trying to create a new way for friends to chat. He was actually developing a service system for Vodafone to send notifications to customers. Talk about an accidental revolution!  It wasn't until Nokia added SMS to their phones in 1993 that texting started becoming what we know today. And now? We send about 60 BILLION texts every day. #tech #technology #stem #techexplained " fetchpriority="auto" decoding="async" src="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/tos-maliva-p-0068/oYfnWORBEyDZumuEU8FAlEACBTAAIQCfvEAJAA~tplv-dmt-logom:tos-useast2a-v-0068/owIqGAG8mBeeBAD0mRkzkQJIABeLERdYFIAACf.image?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=oDh%2B%2Bo%2FniLzWezNlBVZ0WHLjGGU%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=-" imagex-type="react" imagex-version="0.3.10" srcset="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/tos-maliva-p-0068/oYfnWORBEyDZumuEU8FAlEACBTAAIQCfvEAJAA~tplv-dmt-logom:tos-useast2a-v-0068/owIqGAG8mBeeBAD0mRkzkQJIABeLERdYFIAACf.image?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=oDh%2B%2Bo%2FniLzWezNlBVZ0WHLjGGU%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 1x, https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/tos-maliva-p-0068/oYfnWORBEyDZumuEU8FAlEACBTAAIQCfvEAJAA~tplv-dmt-logom:tos-useast2a-v-0068/owIqGAG8mBeeBAD0mRkzkQJIABeLERdYFIAACf.image?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=oDh%2B%2Bo%2FniLzWezNlBVZ0WHLjGGU%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 2x" style="position: absolute; inset: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px; border: none; margin: auto; display: block; width: 0px; height: 0px; min-width: 100%; max-width: 100%; min-height: 100%; max-height: 100%;">

<img alt="Tiff in Tech 使用 Palali Music 的 sonido original 创作的 99% of the internet runs through cables under water. But why wouldn't we just use satellites? It comes down to three main things: First - it comes down to latency. That's the time it takes for your data to make the trip. Through satellites? Your signal has to travel all the way to space and back While cables take a shortcut across the ocean. That's why when I send this message to someone in Europe, it only takes about 100 milliseconds through a cable. Through a satellite? More like 700 milliseconds. Second - these cables are data powerhouses. A single modern cable can carry up to 200 terabits per second. That's like downloading 25,000 HD movies... every second. And third - they're actually more reliable than satellites. They're protected from weather, solar storms, and space debris. Though occasionally they do get attacked by sharks. Yes, really. But that's a story for another video! #stem #tech #techexplained #technology #coding " fetchpriority="auto" decoding="async" src="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/tos-maliva-p-0068/o4IjGgIlKBDfA1GeEge3LFASAHEcOAsXC9yO6I~tplv-dmt-logom:tos-useast2a-v-0068/os60XQABvBt1A4EpAliZNBnAiQ2XBO6iImoEU.image?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=LQ%2BXcAXfHEJX7mLriz6%2FTxfWaEA%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=-" imagex-type="react" imagex-version="0.3.10" srcset="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/tos-maliva-p-0068/o4IjGgIlKBDfA1GeEge3LFASAHEcOAsXC9yO6I~tplv-dmt-logom:tos-useast2a-v-0068/os60XQABvBt1A4EpAliZNBnAiQ2XBO6iImoEU.image?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=LQ%2BXcAXfHEJX7mLriz6%2FTxfWaEA%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 1x, https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/tos-maliva-p-0068/o4IjGgIlKBDfA1GeEge3LFASAHEcOAsXC9yO6I~tplv-dmt-logom:tos-useast2a-v-0068/os60XQABvBt1A4EpAliZNBnAiQ2XBO6iImoEU.image?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=LQ%2BXcAXfHEJX7mLriz6%2FTxfWaEA%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 2x" style="position: absolute; inset: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px; border: none; margin: auto; display: block; width: 0px; height: 0px; min-width: 100%; max-width: 100%; min-height: 100%; max-height: 100%;">

<img alt="Tiff in Tech 使用 Tiff in Tech 的 original sound 创作的 Did you know your private browser mode isn't really keeping you private at all? Let's break down what actually happens when you open a private browsing window. Your browser creates a temporary session - no previous cookies, no browsing history, no saved passwords. When you close the window, all of that session data disappears from your device. That's it. But here's the crucial part: Your internet service provider still sees all your traffic. Your school or workplace network still logs every site you visit. And the websites themselves? They know exactly when you arrive and what you do there. It's similar to using a store but asking them not to save your receipt. The security cameras are still recording, the payment processor still sees your transaction, and the store still knows a customer came in - they just won't have it in their local records. What makes this even more significant is how companies can still track you in private mode using your IP address and something called browser fingerprinting - the unique way your browser and device identify themselves to websites. Even without cookies, these technical signatures can reveal who you are. Send this to someone who might need this reminder! #tech #technology #stem #techexplained " fetchpriority="auto" decoding="async" src="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/og6AwySfAQVRpJkdGeeIFgLBrIQcIALJADAkeG?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=NyI%2BeZN1%2F4o%2BZhMkiCrlLnp8evo%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=-" imagex-type="react" imagex-version="0.3.10" srcset="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/og6AwySfAQVRpJkdGeeIFgLBrIQcIALJADAkeG?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=NyI%2BeZN1%2F4o%2BZhMkiCrlLnp8evo%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 1x, https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/obj/tos-maliva-p-0068/og6AwySfAQVRpJkdGeeIFgLBrIQcIALJADAkeG?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=NyI%2BeZN1%2F4o%2BZhMkiCrlLnp8evo%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 2x" style="position: absolute; inset: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px; border: none; margin: auto; display: block; width: 0px; height: 0px; min-width: 100%; max-width: 100%; min-height: 100%; max-height: 100%;">

<img alt="Tiff in Tech 使用 Tiff in Tech 的 original sound 创作的 Why are some time zones 30 minutes off? And what does that have to do with computers freaking out about leap seconds? Here's the thing - the whole world used to run on local time. Noon was when the sun was highest in your specific location. But then trains happened. Railway companies needed standardized time to make schedules work. So in 1884, we divided the world into 24 time zones. Clean and simple, right? Not exactly. Because some countries said &quot;we're gonna do our own thing.&quot; India split the difference between two zones with a +5:30 offset. Nepal went even further with +5:45. And computers? They HATE this. See, computers need precise time for everything from security certificates to financial transactions. They use UTC - Universal Coordinated Time. But Earth's rotation isn't perfectly consistent. So scientists occasionally add &quot;leap seconds&quot; to keep atomic clocks synchronized with Earth's rotation. The last time this happened, some major websites crashed. So next time you check your phone's clock, remember - you're looking at a system built to handle trains, political compromise, planets, AND computers all at once #tech #technology #coding #stem " fetchpriority="auto" decoding="async" src="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/tos-maliva-p-0068/oAfWAcKBkzRUEoi0iNhi9CQBBTACsIIkR7EAAg~tplv-dmt-logom:tos-useast2a-v-0068/oMvQjpEtAmiEIvJnRTmCB7mfVEQWIAFJADAZfD.image?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=Rm%2BZNFYceQj5acn2pNPBXTZR3zI%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=-" imagex-type="react" imagex-version="0.3.10" srcset="https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/tos-maliva-p-0068/oAfWAcKBkzRUEoi0iNhi9CQBBTACsIIkR7EAAg~tplv-dmt-logom:tos-useast2a-v-0068/oMvQjpEtAmiEIvJnRTmCB7mfVEQWIAFJADAZfD.image?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=Rm%2BZNFYceQj5acn2pNPBXTZR3zI%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 1x, https://p16-sign-va.tiktokcdn.com/tos-maliva-p-0068/oAfWAcKBkzRUEoi0iNhi9CQBBTACsIIkR7EAAg~tplv-dmt-logom:tos-useast2a-v-0068/oMvQjpEtAmiEIvJnRTmCB7mfVEQWIAFJADAZfD.image?lk3s=81f88b70&amp;x-expires=1748566800&amp;x-signature=Rm%2BZNFYceQj5acn2pNPBXTZR3zI%3D&amp;shp=81f88b70&amp;shcp=- 2x" style="position: absolute; inset: 0px; box-sizing: border-box; padding: 0px; border: none; margin: auto; display: block; width: 0px; height: 0px; min-width: 100%; max-width: 100%; min-height: 100%; max-height: 100%;">
